==================================================
   OpenFOAM 13 – Modular Solver Architecture
==================================================

1. foamRun overview
-------------------
foamRun is the *generic driver executable* for all modern OpenFOAM solvers.
It defines the time-loop structure (predictor–corrector scheme) and
dynamically loads a solver module specified in system/controlDict:

    solver  shockFluid;

or via command line:

    foamRun -solver shockFluid

foamRun itself contains no PDEs — it provides the framework for running them.

--------------------------------------------------
Main tasks performed by foamRun:
1. Reads system/controlDict
2. Loads the specified solver module library (libshockFluid.so)
3. Instantiates the solver class (e.g. Foam::solvers::shockFluid)
4. Enters the PIMPLE-style time loop and calls solver methods in order.

--------------------------------------------------
Simplified call sequence:

You run:
   foamRun -solver shockFluid
        │
        ▼
foamRun main()
   ├─ reads controlDict → solverName = "shockFluid"
   ├─ solver::load("shockFluid")      ← dynamic linking
   ├─ solverPtr = solver::New(...)    ← constructs shockFluid object
   └─ enters time loop:
          ├─ solver.preSolve()
          ├─ solver.prePredictor()
          ├─ solver.momentumTransportPredictor()
          ├─ solver.thermophysicalTransportPredictor()
          ├─ solver.momentumTransportCorrector()
          ├─ solver.thermophysicalTransportCorrector()
          ├─ solver.postSolve()
          └─ write results

==================================================
2. The solver module (e.g. shockFluid)
==================================================

Folder:
    applications/modules/shockFluid/

Files:
    shockFluid.C / shockFluid.H
    momentumPredictor.C
    pressureCorrector.C
    thermophysicalPredictor.C
    fluxPredictor.C
    correctDensity.C
    moveMesh.C
    setRDeltaT.C
    Make/

--------------------------------------------------
Role of the module:
- Registers itself with OpenFOAM:
    addToRunTimeSelectionTable(solver, shockFluid, fvMesh);
- Provides implementations for all virtual methods called by foamRun.
- Defines what happens in each time step.

Example function meanings:
  preSolve()                      → update mesh, CFL number
  prePredictor()                  → compute fluxes, densities
  momentumTransportPredictor()    → solve momentum PDE
  thermophysicalTransportPredictor() → solve energy/temperature PDE
  momentumTransportCorrector()    → apply pressure/continuity correction
  thermophysicalTransportCorrector() → apply thermal correction
  postSolve()                     → write output, cleanup

--------------------------------------------------
Each PDE is assembled using finite-volume operators (fvm::ddt, fvm::div, etc.)
inside the predictor/corrector source files.

Example (from momentumPredictor.C):
    fvVectorMatrix UEqn
    (
        fvm::ddt(rho, U)
      + fvm::div(phi, U)
      - fvm::laplacian(muEff, U)
    );

==================================================
3. Where the physics and coefficients come from
==================================================
- thermophysicalProperties → defines fluid models and viscosity laws.
- turbulence models, equations of state, etc. loaded via runtime selection.
- Each field (p, U, T, rho, phi) read or created by the solver constructor.

--------------------------------------------------
Key point:
The PDE coefficients (nu, mu, rho, etc.) are *not hardcoded*.
They are computed by model classes (psiThermo, momentumTransport, etc.)
that are instantiated in the solver constructor.

==================================================
4. Universal structure for all domains
==================================================
All solvers (fluid, solid, multiphase, etc.) follow the same call sequence.
The difference lies in which predictor/corrector methods they implement.

For example:

  - shockFluid → compressible Navier–Stokes (with energy)
  - incompressibleFluid → incompressible Navier–Stokes
  - solid → mechanical equilibrium ∇·σ = 0
  - heatTransfer → ∇·(k∇T) = 0

All share the same foamRun time-loop skeleton.

==================================================
5. Summary hierarchy
==================================================

foamRun (driver)
   ↓
solver module (e.g. shockFluid)
   ↓
  ├─ Builds thermodynamics & transport models
  ├─ Defines predictor/corrector methods
   ↓
finite-volume operators (fvm/fvc)
   ↓
OpenFOAM field data (p, U, T, rho, etc.)

--------------------------------------------------
foamRun  →  framework and time control  
shockFluid  →  PDE definitions and physics  
Models  →  compute μ(T), ρ(p,T), Cp(T), etc.

